		<h1 class="ribbon-left">Risk Management Standards for Energy Market Participants</h1>
		<br /><br /><br /><br />
		<h2 id="executive-summary" class="numbering_exclude">Executive Summary</h2>

		<p>The CCRO’s membership of expert practitioners has worked together for almost a decade now, developing and publishing “best practices” that an energy firm may choose to deploy in pursuit of the most effective management of risks inherent to its commercial activities. In contrast, this CCRO working group has identified the spectrum of critical risk-related issues that must be addressed, these being fundamental to basic risk management. This Risk Management Standards (RMS) document brings together that spectrum of issues and addresses them with a comprehensive list of twenty-seven “risk management standards”. We hold these standards as necessary to make effective management of energy risks possible for any energy firm.</p>
		<p>At the highest level, the risk standards are organized into:</p>
		<ol class="toc">
		  <li>Independent Risk Governance <a href="#governance"><i class="icon-share"></i></a></li>
		  <li>Risk Policies and Procedures <a href="#policies-and-procedures"><i class="icon-share"></i></a></li>
		  <li>Qualifications and Training <a href="#qualifications-and-training"><i class="icon-share"></i></a></li>
		  <li>Risk Management Infrastructure <a href="#risk-management-infrastructure"><i class="icon-share"></i></a></li>
		</ol>

		<p>The CCRO asserts that energy firms should meet or exceed these “standards” in order to ensure that effective risk management is within reach of their company’s management.</p>
		<p>For each of these sections this paper briefly introduces the issues, and lists related standards. Much more detailed information and discussion of these topics can be found in other published CCRO white papers. Defined terms are capitalized and the definitions section can be found at the end of the document.</p>
		<p>This Executive Summary is intended to provide a context regarding the development of the Risk Management Standards, but should not be interpreted as a part of the standards. In particular, this Executive Summary should not be construed to add to, detract from or modify in any way the interpretation of the standards as written.</p>
		<p>These Risk Management Standards have been developed by the CCRO at the request of their membership and other interested energy industry participants, and not at the request of any regulator. They have been developed to meet the needs of industry participants, without consideration for any particular regulator or regulatory process.</p>

		<h3 class="numbering_exclude">Independent Risk Governance <span class="pull-right">Standards 1 to 6</span></h3>
		<p>Independent governance over risk establishes an organizational foundation for risk management. When tested, a firm’s risk management effectiveness is ultimately limited by how firmly these governance standards are in place. Governance duties are assigned to the Governing Body, an optional Management Committee, individuals engaged in Commercial Activities, and to certain individuals Independent from Commercial Activities.</p>
		<p>The Governing Body of the firm has ultimate authority and responsibility for authorizing the Commercial Activities of the firm, and must therefore be sufficiently informed and involved.</p>
		<p>The standards detail these general themes:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>The Governing Body will Periodically re-affirm its understanding of the firm’s risks and the firm’s capacity to fulfill potential future financial and physical obligations that may result.</li>
			<li>The Governing Body will authorize Commercial Activities and set the maximum acceptable level of specific risks that those activities may generate for the firm.</li>
		</ul>
  
		<p>The Governing Body may choose to delegate to a Management Committee a list of more detailed necessary risk governance duties. The standards detail these general themes:</p>
		<ul>
		  <li>Understanding, reviewing, modifying, mandating, responding to, and authorizing various risk matters on an on-going basis.</li>
		  <li>Periodically reporting risk management performance to the Governing Body</li>
		</ul>
  
		<p>Individuals Independent of Commercial Activities must perform those activities that are essential to accurate identification, measurement, and independent monitoring of risks.</p>

		<p>The standards detail these general themes:</p>
		<ul>
		  <li>Validation of transaction information and related market information</li>
		  <li>Valuation of transactions and development of systems used for that purpose</li>
		  <li>Measurement of risks and development of systems used for that purpose</li>
		  <li>Reporting of performance and compliance with limits&nbsp;</li>
		</ul>
		
	
		<h3 class="numbering_exclude">Risk Policies and Procedures <span class="pull-right">Standards 7 to 22</span></h3>

		<p>Risk policies and procedures are documented protocols, which serve to guide individuals regarding execution of relevant day-to-day activities. These protocols, critical to risk management, pertain to all organizational levels and risk-related functions across the firm. These standards generally address credit, market, and operations risks, as well as the reliability and regularity of risk reporting. The standards detail these general themes:</p>

		<ul>
		  <li>The firm’s documented risk policies, approved by the Governing Body, assign responsibilities for risk oversight and define required controls related to such oversight.</li>
		  <li>Risk policies should include the following risk controls: required risk analyses and reporting, specific limits to market and credit risk, authorization of counter-parties and associated credit terms and limits, and monitoring of all transaction compliance issues.</li>
		  <li>Risk procedures should require that the confirmation and timely capture of transaction information into a system for analyses, valuation, and risk reporting be defined and meet standards for independence and robustness.</li>
		  <li>Policies and procedures should also require that price information used must be validated and verified independently.</li>
		  <li>A rich set of standards is provided to assure robust, insightful risk analyses and reporting.</li>
		</ul>
    
		<h3 class="numbering_exclude">Qualified Personnel <span class="pull-right">Standards 23 and 24</span></h3>
		<p>Underpinning the success of the risk framework is the widespread understanding and daily usage of key risk management concepts throughout the firm. It is critical to ensure personnel are qualified and experienced. Since qualifications must develop as the firm’s risk taking activities develop; it is impossible to separate the need for qualifications from the need for on-going education and focused training.</p>
		<blockquote><em>In a risk-aware organization, the quality of the education program is readily apparent in the consistent manner that communication and discussion of risks is undertaken.</em></blockquote>
		<p>The standards address qualification and training requirements for individuals involved in Commercial Activities, oversight of Commercial Activities and Associated Risks, and the Governing Body.</p>
		
		<h3 class="numbering_exclude">Risk Management Infrastructure <span class="pull-right">Standards 25 to 27</span></h3>
		<p>The objective of Risk Management Systems is to provide the security and data integrity to properly serve the business. The systems used may vary by company to reflect differences in business objectives, markets, and products associated with a company’s energy transactions.A proper risk infrastructure is necessary to provide accurate and timely information for decision-makers. The risk infrastructure is typically a marriage of technology, business process and communication.</p>
		<p>The standards address the following themes:</p>
		<ul>
		  <li>A Risk Management System must capture transaction details, and support operational requirements, risk metric calculations, and financial reporting.</li>
		  <li>There must be policies and controls that protect the security and integrity of the data and information within the system.</li>
		  <li>The risk infrastructure must provide the capability to monitor, aggregate and present relevant information on a timely basis to stakeholders.</li>
		</ul>
	
